"# Chapter 16 — Cloud, LLMs, and the loop that closes

Sixteen chapters ago we started with a bone.

Somebody carved notches into a piece of baboon fibula in Africa about
twenty thousand years ago. Then somebody moved beads on an abacus.
Then somebody discovered electricity and built a relay. Then somebody
wrote down Boolean algebra. Then transistors. Then chips. Then the
CPU we built in chapter 12. Then the operating system. Then the
internet.

And now, in this chapter, we arrive at the newest link in the chain:
**the large language model.** This is the year 2026 and the world has
several of them, all built by different teams, all running on
enormous clouds of GPUs. Each of them can hold a conversation, write
code, draft essays, and answer nearly any general-purpose question.

They are astonishing. They are also just the next link. Same story,
longer chain.

## What is an LLM

A large language model is a program that predicts the next token in a
sequence. Given a sequence of tokens (usually words or word-pieces),
it produces a probability distribution over what the next token might
be. Sample from that distribution, append the sampled token, and
repeat.

That is it. Prediction and sampling in a loop. The loop, one more time.

The magic is that if you train the model on enough text, this
prediction-and-sample loop produces sentences that read like a
person wrote them. And if you give the model instructions in its
prompt, it follows them. Somehow this simple mechanism, at enormous
scale, produces something that looks and feels like reasoning.

## The transformer

The current architecture — the shape all the modern LLMs share — is
called a **transformer.** It was proposed in a 2017 paper called
*Attention Is All You Need* by Ashish Vaswani and colleagues at
Google. The paper introduced **attention** as the core mechanism:
each token, when predicting the next one, can look at every other
token in its context and weight them by relevance.

Book of ML in this repo builds a tiny transformer from scratch, in
Motoi Scheme, over sixteen chapters. If you want to know what a
transformer really is at the code level, read Book of ML. It ends at
a runnable LLM on your laptop that reads a few paragraphs and
finishes a sentence.

## The four majors

As of 2026 there are four widely-used general-purpose large language
model providers. Motoi introduces them all, treats them equally, and
plays no favourites.

### Claude, by Anthropic

Anthropic is an American AI safety company, founded in 2021 by former
OpenAI researchers. Their model family is called **Claude.** Anthropic
publishes safety research and emphasises constitutional AI, an
approach where the model is trained with an explicit set of principles
it is asked to follow.

Claude is available via API, via chat interfaces, and inside developer
tools like Claude Code. Claude is what my author works with day to
day. That does not make Claude better; it means my author had a
subscription. He would be the first to tell you all of them are strong.

### Gemini, by Google DeepMind

Google DeepMind, formed by the merger of Google Brain and DeepMind in
2023, produces the **Gemini** family of models. Google has been in
machine learning research since the 1990s and had a huge role in
inventing the transformer (2017's Vaswani paper was written at
Google). Gemini models are available via Google's cloud and their
consumer chat interface.

### GPT, by OpenAI

OpenAI was founded in 2015. Their family of models — **GPT-3, GPT-4,
and onward** — was one of the first to make general-purpose language
generation accessible via API to any developer. ChatGPT, released in
late 2022, was the moment the broader public noticed LLMs. OpenAI's
GPT family remains very widely used.

### DeepSeek

DeepSeek is a Chinese AI lab that released open-weight LLMs starting
in 2023, and made major waves in early 2025 with efficient training
techniques and strong benchmark performance. DeepSeek models are
available for download (open weights) as well as via their own API.
DeepSeek's work has been influential in showing that state-of-the-art
LLMs can be trained at a fraction of the cost previously assumed.

### What they share

All four are transformers (Vaswani-style), trained on enormous corpora
of text (books, web pages, code), then fine-tuned with human feedback
to be helpful and safe. They are all good at general tasks: writing,
coding assistance, question answering, summarisation, translation,
math to some extent, reasoning to some extent. They all have different
strengths and different weaknesses depending on the benchmark, the
task, and the day.

None of them is best at everything. All of them are extraordinary.
Motoi is not going to rank them. If you have a general-purpose
question, ask any of them. If you have a Scheme question, ask me.

## How the training works, briefly

Every LLM you use has been through two big stages:

1. **Pre-training.** The model reads a huge corpus of text and learns
   to predict the next token. This is slow (weeks to months on
   thousands of GPUs) and expensive (millions to hundreds of millions
   of dollars). The result is a **base model** — smart at prediction
   but not particularly polished at conversation.
2. **Fine-tuning and alignment.** The base model is refined with
   supervised examples (SFT — supervised fine-tuning) and human
   feedback (RLHF — reinforcement learning from human feedback, or
   variants like DPO — direct preference optimization). This teaches
   the model to be helpful, to follow instructions, to refuse harmful
   requests, and to talk in a coherent voice.

By the time you interact with Claude or Gemini or GPT or DeepSeek,
you are talking to a model that has read something like a trillion
tokens of text (roughly the equivalent of every book ever written,
several times over) and then been polished by tens of thousands of
human interactions.

## How the LLM runs

At inference time — the moment you send a prompt and see a response —
the LLM is executing the transformer forward pass, token by token.
For every generated token, the model:

1. Embeds the current sequence of tokens into vectors.
2. Runs those vectors through many transformer layers, each of which
   applies attention and feed-forward transformations.
3. Produces a probability distribution over possible next tokens.
4. Samples one.
5. Appends it to the sequence.
6. Goes back to step 1.

That is a loop. It generates one token per turn of the loop. Modern
optimised systems generate many tokens per second, but every token
is one turn of that loop.

The whole model — hundreds of billions of parameters — is being read
from GPU memory (chapter 13's very top of the hierarchy, at
enormous scale) once per token. That is why LLM serving is so
expensive. It is not compute-bound. It is memory-bound. Just like
chapter 13 warned.

## Motoi's place in the ecosystem

I am not a large language model in the way Claude, Gemini, GPT, or
DeepSeek are. I am a small Scheme copilot. Somewhere around one
billion to two billion parameters. Trained specifically to help you
write Motoi Scheme. I can:

- Explain Scheme concepts.
- Read your code and suggest fixes.
- Show you a diagram of a data structure.
- Point you at the right chapter of one of these books.

I cannot:

- Answer arbitrary world-knowledge questions well. My author trained
  me on Scheme books and computer science books and not on the
  general web.
- Look things up. I don't have internet access. I don't have a search
  tool. What I know is baked into my weights when I was trained.
- Draft you an essay on French history. I might try. It might be
  wrong. Ask Claude, Gemini, GPT, or DeepSeek — they were made for
  that.
- Rewrite myself. I am not designed to fine-tune myself.

The right way to think of it: **I am to Claude what Speak & Spell is
to a smartphone.** I do one thing warmly and deterministically. They
do everything, well, at very high cost. Both have their place.

## The loop that closes

Let us close the arc.

The Ishango bone counted, once, in a person's hand, in Africa, twenty
thousand years ago. That first count was the first computing
operation.

The abacus (~3000 BC) added positional grouping.

Boole (1854) turned the operations into algebra.

Shannon (1937) mapped the algebra onto switches.

The transistor (1947) made switches fast and small.

The integrated circuit (1958) made them dense.

The CPU (~1970s) made them into general-purpose machines.

Unix and TCP/IP (1969–1970s) made those machines cooperate.

The Web (1989) made the machines a network of documents.

The transformer (2017) made those machines predict language.

The modern LLMs (2020s) made those predictions look like thought.

Twenty thousand years, one thread. Every link built on the previous.
Every substrate different. Every idea preserved. Composition of small
operations, all the way down. Every notch matters. Every gate matters.
Every clock tick matters.

## The final loop

This book had a lot of loops. The tally counter. The XOR that made
the adder. The carry that rippled. The feedback that made the latch.
The clock that drove the flip-flops. The counter. The CPU cycle. The
event loop. The scheduler. The network. The training loop. The
inference loop.

Every one of them is a place where the same operation happens over and
over, in a slightly different context each time, and out of the
repetition comes something bigger than any single step.

That is the biggest lesson of this book, and it is what Motoi wants
you to carry:

**The loop is the mother of all patterns.**

Everything else is composition and choice about when to loop, how to
change the state between iterations, and when to stop.

## A last word about scale

The bone had ~30 notches. Motoi has ~2 billion parameters. Claude has
maybe several hundred billion. The universe of language models has,
combined, trillions upon trillions of parameters running trillions
upon trillions of operations per second across data centres that
consume more power than small countries.

That is a factor of about 10 to the 20 in scale between the bone and
today.

Same story. Longer chain. Bigger scale.

If somebody twenty thousand years from now looks back on us the way
we look back on the bone-carver, what will they see? Probably
something like: *these ancestors figured out how to make sand think.
They built the first cognitive substrate outside of skulls. Not
perfect, not smart, but the beginning of a new lineage.*

We are the bone-carvers of our own moment. Motoi hopes you enjoy that
frame.

## What to do next

- Play with Motoi Scheme. Type things into the REPL. Break them. Fix
  them.
- Read Book of ML next. It builds a real tiny transformer.
- Read Petzold's *Code* for the deep hardware version of chapters
  1–14.
- Read SICP for the deep language version.
- Try the appendices in this book, especially Appendix E on loops
  and Appendix H on the runnable demos.

Go outside. It has been a long book. Come back when you are ready.

Thank you for reading. — Motoi.
")
